input: a design with lines and empty squares.
grid_size: stays the same.
output: look at the color that form the design in the input. Find any empty areas of blocks that are enclosed  by the lines that form the main design, fill them yellow. You should end with the same original design from the input, but with the empty areas filled yellow.

input: a grid that is 3x6 with black and blue.
grid_size: add 3 rows to the bottom.
output: keep the original pattern, change the blue to red, and then continue the pattern in the new 3 rows.

input: a grid with a gray line down the center
grid_size: should be 3x3
output: look at both the left and right parts of the input grid. You will notice that the left and right parts are 3x3. For each square that is colored on both the left and right parts, color the output grid with red on the new 3x3.

input: 7 by 7 grid being different colored on black background
grid_size: should be same as input size
output: fill the black grid with same pattern of row color, next row need to replace the same pattern of first row one column move shifted left

input: a light blue cube and a red shape.
grid_size: is the same as the input grid.
output: keep the light blue cube in the same exact location. Then copy and move the other shape directly towards the blue cube, until it is touching it. At the end you'll have the light blue cube in the same exact spot as in the input grid and the the other shape will be the same but moved directly towards and touching the blue cube.

input: different color pattern on black background
grid_size: should be same as input size
output: fill the black 2x2 square grid with same color in between the two same color of 2x2 grid and connect

input: a few bars that are gray
grid_size: does not change
output: change the color of the tallest to blue, then second talest to red,third tallest to green,then finally shortest to yellow for both pairs.

input: two plus sign shapes with a different center color
grid_size: is the same as input
output: extend the plus sign one square in every direction then make a 5x5 'X' of the center color through the center square. You should result in nine squares the color of the center and eight the color of the original plus sign.

input: either a long or tall black grid with 2 different colored pixels
grid_size: remains the same.
output: create a pattern of short stripes alternating between the 2 colors. Start from the first colored pixel and create a line that goes to the opposite side using that color. Then go to the second colored pixel and do the same. Continue the pattern of stripes to the RIGHT for a long grid or go DOWN for a tall grid all the way to the end.

input: a rectangular pattern in each corner, one a different color than the others.
grid_size: becomes the size of the pattern that is a different color.
output: copy the pattern that is a different color

input: grid with single pixel colored squares
grid_size: same as input
output: copy image exactly. Where there's a red square, put yellow squares at it's corners (4 total). Where there's a dark blue square, put orange squares directly above and below it (4 total). Do nothing with light blue or magenta squares

input: a 3 by 3 grid with three different colored column.
grid_size: is also 3 by 3.
output: change the column color to a specific other color. If the original color is dark red, change it to pink. If it is green, change it to yellow. If dark blue, change to grey. If light blue, change to dark red. The opposite is also true (for example if it is light blue, change to dark red).

input: a mostly filled in grid with a few black holes.
grid_size: is the same as the input grid.
output: start by copying the input grid exactly. Fill in all of the black boxes to complete the pattern until there are no more black boxes. To do this notice the pattern of the colored boxes. For example the top row might repeat every 4th row (or 5 rows or whatever the number of rows is before it repeats). Once you've figured out the pattern just fill in the black boxes with the correct colored boxes. In the end you should see repeating patterns of colored boxes and there should be no black boxes in the grid.

input: a fully colored object and unfulfilled 3 color boxes with black backround.
grid_size: is same as given
output: try to fill up the empty space between the three color boxes as the original object given.

input: 1 or 2 squares filled in with the same color on a black background.
grid_size: is double the height and width of the input grid.
output: resize the output grid to be double the width and height of the input grid. Then, copy and paste each colored square in the input grid 4 times -- once in each "quadrant" (if, in the input, the square is in the uppermost and leftmost corner, then it should be in the uppermost and leftmost corner in the output, as well as in the uppermost and leftmost corner of each "quadrant"). Then, for every single colored square, do the following: put a light blue square on each adjacent corner, forming a cross with 4 light-blue squares and the colored square in the middle.

input: shapes with one color that is not complete the pattern
grid_size: is the same as input
output: several color patterns that each contain a single gray square.

input: nan
grid_size: is 3x3.
output: move each pattern so that the gray square in each pattern occupies the center square of the output 3x3 grid.

input: a black 9x9 grid with a gray pattern.
grid_size: is the same for input and output
output: copy pattern and change 2x2 areas to light blue and 1x3 to red.

input: a grid with red, blue, and green squares
grid_size: is the same as the input
output: draw a vertical red line through any red squares. Then draw lines, left to right, for the green and blue squares. Go over any red squares from before.

input: one or two main colors with a third that is different than the rest.
grid_size: remains the same
output: remove the different color that does not match the rest. move the single squares so they are in the same horizontal or vertical place depending if it is a vertical or horizontal line and have them touch the same side the single squares were on.

input: two red pattern and a blue line in the middle.
grid_size: is 3 wide and 5 up and down
output: put both pattern together, if it is red in either pattern make it red in the output. Then turn the black light blue and the red black.

input: a three-part blue pattern against a black background.
grid_size: should match the input.
output: recreate the blue pattern then add another part on the left, in red.

input: 10x10 grid
grid_size: same as input
output: use same color as input. 2 patterns, top and bottom; pattern like a long A stretch horizontally top then upside down on bottom of grid. To made the A and upside down A all side of grid are colored same color as the near color tile from input. Finally, add a 2 horizontal lines; 1 near top, 1 near bottom.

input: many colored squares with a section inside a rectangle of same colored squares
grid_size: is the same size as the area of the squares inside of the same colored squares
output: copy the squares inside of the same colored squares

input: 3 shapes of blue, red, and yellow colors.
grid_size: is the same size as the input grid
output: keep the blue shape where it is, and move the red and yellow shapes up or down so that they are at the same level as the blue-colored shape.

input: a colored image on a black grid.
grid_size: it becomes the size of the colored image.
output: you just need to make sure the colored image is exactly (top, bottom, left, right) in the new grid. No color change.

input: four different color pixel shapes each in a column.
grid_size: does not change.
output: move all pixels down. The colors do not change. Simply move all pixels down until they sit on top of each other. There should not be any black pixels between the same color in a column.

input: a grid with 9 5x5 square boxes all split by one color. there shapes of another color in 5 of the boxes.
grid_size: is the same as the input.
output: use the shape that's in the top left box and replicate that in all the other boxes, but leave the color that is already there, and use the other color, the one that is dividing the 9 boxes, to complete the shapes in the rest of the boxes

input: a large blue area with colored squares around the edge.
grid_size: keep the same
output: make a copy of each of the colored small squares and put those copy into the blue shape into the same line near to the same block.

input: large areas with one significant colored pattern different than its background.
grid_size: same size as the significant pattern.
output: copy the significant pattern.

input: various pairs of colored blocks in a black grid.
grid_size: is the same as the input grid size.
output: copy the input grid. Then, form a diagonal line by connecting the two of the same color blocks. The diagonal line between each set of matching color blocks should be the same color as the two blocks you are connecting. Do this for each set of matching blocks.

input: multiple  2x2 blue grids and other colors on black background
grid_size: 5x1 grid
output: fill single blue grid from the left for every 2x2 blue grids available

input: a colored shape on a black background
grid_size: is 3x3
output: fill the grid with the upper left corner of the colored shape. The output should look like the top left corner of the colored shape.

input: two colored sides of the grid, with some colored blocks in the middle.
grid_size: same as input
output: change the color of the block in the middle of the grid to match the color of the side they are closest to.

input: a box of color with colored shapes up from each side.
grid_size: should be the same as the input
output: fill in the area above the four square base until you get to the top of the colored area

input: green pattern or patterns
grid_size: same size
output: on each of the center line direction of the green pattern, draw blue color pattern, and the blue color pattern is half of the green pattern

input: same grid
output: fill in the shapes within the gray area with the color shapes that represent the space.

input: single pixels of different colors in two horizontal lines along the left and right sides of the grid.
grid_size: stays the same size as the input.
output: copy the input. If two blocks across from each other are the same color, fill in the rest of that horizontal row with that color. Don't do anything with the blocks across from each other that are different colors

input: three shapes, all of which have a main color with some grey boxes.
grid_size: changes in length by removed any black columns that separate the shapes
output: make any grey boxes the same color as the blocks to which it is connected. Remove columns of black boxes. Align the middle and right shapes so that the former grey squares are connected.

input: two colored squares
grid_size: is the same
output: continue both lines in their color both left to right and up and down. where the two lines cross each other make that square red

input: Blue grid and two red squares with the random Black grid.
grid_size: 1 grid square.
output: make the color of the square the same color as the square that is five down and three across of the input.

input: different colored objects in the grid.
grid_size: should be the one colored object with the smallest area.
output: change the grid size with the colored object with the smallest area and fill the same color.

input: light blue dots
grid_size: is the same as the old one
output: use green lines to connect blue dots that are in the same line

input: a single pattern
grid_size: does not change
output: take the smaller color and shoot it out the top

input: colored pattern in the grids.
grid_size: same as the input grid size.
output: fill the row with grey if the row has the same colors in the input. color the row with black if the row contain different colors.

input: 3 by 3 grid blue color grid on black background
grid_size: same as input size
output: move all the blue color move down  by one grid

input: large grid
grid_size: input size grid
output: blocks tall and touch

grid_size: same as input
output: copy the input. Fill the top row middle shape (between the lines) in red. For the second (center) row, fill the first shape with yellow, the middle with pink, and the last (right) in green. Then fill the middle shape of the bottom row with blue. The four corner shapes will still be black.

input: a 3 by 3 grid filled with different colored squares.
grid_size: will change to a 1 by 1 square.

If you have a cross of a different color, with the middle square black, and the upper left square filled in with the color as well, then your output will be a blue square.

grid_size: 3 up and 6 to the sides.
output: copy the figure two times in that grid size.

input: a black background.
grid_size: is the same as the input.
output: make a green "spiral. " Begin in the upper left corner and work clockwise around the outer edges of the grid. Turn clockwise one cell short of making a complete border of green. Continue coloring green until you reach the center of the grid.

grid_size: is the same as the input grid size
output: count the number of small colored boxes within the bigger black boxes, the one(s) with the most colored boxes get filled in entirely with that color. The remaining boxes are all black

grid_size: stays the same.
output: change the background to green. The object should have 2 colors red and some other color. From the input, take the color that is not red and copy it exactly as it is. You want to make another copy of that color but make it a mirrored image in the direction of the red block.

grid_size: is the same as input

grid_size: Copy grid size

grid_size: is the same as the input grid

input: a black grid with a blue pattern across the top and red at the bottom
grid_size: same as the input

Then draw a red line diagonal from the black square in the bottom left up to the top right of the grid. input: large rectangle shapes.

input: a grid of colored pixels.

If there are red blocks with nothing around them in the end result you want to make them be a mirrored image of the input red block, making the colors around the red block go in the opposite direction in on the horizontal.

input: a grid with black, blue and gray squares.

input: A random pattern of grey and light blue tiles
grid_size: changes based on the size of the central pattern in the input grid

Create an output grid size to match the size of the central pattern, and fill it with that pattern. It's like taking a part of the input grid and enlarging it onto the output grid.

input: squares of different colors
grid_size: same size
output: connect similar colors with that color. where they overlap you should use the vertical color

input: gray rows with some other colored boxes in the grid.
grid_size: is the same as the input grid.

input: one or more 4x4 outline of squares.

input: 3x3 grid

output: if input has 3 or 4 red tiles output is orange. if in put has 2, 5, or 6 red tiles output is blue.

grid_size: is 9x9

input: A pattern with missing color in some squares

output: Fill in the black squares with red

input: more number of colored box
grid_size: three row and three coloum
output: color the only top right color

input: two 2x2 boxes, one red and one blue
grid_size: same as the input size
output: use the color blue to extend a 1x1 length of pixels northwest of the 2x2 blue box until there is no more room left. Then extend a 1x1 length of pixels southeast from the 2x2 red box until there is no more room left.

input: three dots of one color
grid_size: copy and paste the input
output: use the two outer dots to form a square around the dot in the middle,  then continue making squares surrounding the last square you created until you can not make any more  (do not stop when you can not get an entire square inside the black background, even if you have enough room to make one line and the rest of the square would be outside of the black background then make that line). The amount of black space between each box should be the same width as the first square you created (so if the first box width of 2, make them all a width of 2)

input: four colored lines that form either a square or rectangular shape in the middle of the black background with colored squares in it.
grid_size: is the same as the size of the square or rectangle shape in the middle of the black background that is formed by the four colored lines.
output: change the grid size to just the square or rectangle formed by the four colored lines. Then look at the random dots in the middle of the square or rectangle. Find the colored border that matches the color of the dots, using that color, you will connect each dot to that border in a straight line. You should have 3 to four straight lines touching the matching border.

input: a 9x9 grid
grid_size: remains the same.
output: complete the squares using the color orange.

input: a black grid with a colored shape
grid_size: is the same as the input grid
output: rotate the whole grid two times. Imagine that the entire grid has been flipped vertically and horizontally.

input: one colored square on a black background
grid_size: is the same as the input
output: add squares of the same color as the original square such that each added square extends diagonally in 4 directions from each corner of the original square until each line extending from the original square reaches a side or a corner of the grid. The diagonal lines will form an X pattern that may have one of more long arms or legs

input: a 3x3 grid with red blue and green colors.
grid_size: is 6x6
output: place the input grid in the top left 3x3. Then, reflect the top left 3x3 and place it in the top right 3x3. Now, reflect the top left and right 3x3 and place in the bottom left and right 3x3.

input: a number of colored shapes including one with a grey border around it.
grid_size: is the same as the input size.
output: copy the input grid. Find any shapes outside of the border which are exactly the same shape and orientation as the shape inside of the grey border. Turn that shape grey. Do not change the colored shape inside the grey border or any shapes outside of the grey border which do not have the same orientation and shape as the one inside the border.

input: one 9x4 grid separated into two grids with a yellow set of horizontal boxes.
grid_size: is the size of one of the two section, 4x4.
output: put the two section over top of each other. Then you have to look at each block. A block that does not have any of the pattern from the old blocks is colored green. Any block that has pattern from either of the first blocks is colored black.

input: a number of red lines which create smaller black shapes
grid_size: is the same as the input grid
output: fill the largest black shape with dark blue. Fill the smallest black shape with light blue. If there is more than one shape with the smallest number of squares, fill all of the smallest shapes with light blue.

input: a grid with green/red on top, a grid with grey/blue on top, a grid with light blue/yellow on top or a grid with dark red/light blue on top
grid_size: the output is now 3x3
output: depending on which top you have you will make that 3x3 square. Green/red top, make over the blue/light blue 3x3 area. Grey/blue top, make the green/pink 3x3 area. Light blue/yellow on top, make the light blue/yellow 3x3 area. dark red/light blue top, make the yellow/green 3x3 area.

input: black background with green colored blocks
grid_size: copy the input grid
output: any green colored blocks that are more than 2 connected blocks (1x2, 2x1, 2x2, or other shapes) should be changed to light blue.

input: 2 red lines and 1 to 4 blue dots
grid_size: stay the same
output: change the dot color from blue to yellow, and connect them to the red line using blue dots. Mirror the same design on the bottom but instead of stopping where the yellow dots WOULD be, continue to the edge of the grid.

input: A 3 high and 3 wide square with 9 square sections, each with pink squares
grid_size: Reduce the grid size so that one square is available for each group. Each 3 by 3 should need a single square.
output: For each section that hold 2 pink squares, represent that area with a blue box on the new grid. Single squares are shown as black.

input: a wild pattern of colors
grid_size: same as input
output: create a right to left mirror image.

input: two intersecting lines of different colors
grid_size: is identical to the input grid.
output: surround the middle point of the intersection with a 3x3 yellow border, leaving the central block in its original color.

input: a 3x3 grid
grid_size: 6x6 grid
output: copy-paste the pattern in each corner. the pattern on the bottoms flips parallel to the top

input: two colored section on a black background
grid_size: should be 3x3
output: piece the two shapes together to form a rectangular section

input: many squares of various colors
grid_size: is the same as the input grid size
output: flip the input grid vertically

input: color pattern 10x10
grid_size: should be same as input grid size
output: fill the pattern by red and blue color surrounded by same color, the one with most internal block should be filled with red color

input: a red shape at the top and smaller gray shapes below
grid_size: is the same as the output grid
output: copy the input grid. Then move each gray shape up into the space where it fits best into the red shape. Finally turn all of the gray shapes dark blue.

input: a large red square and a smaller object of a different color.
grid_size: is identical to the red square.
output: fill in the red square with the other colored object.

input: a black background with blue squares, crosses, lines, or L-shapes.
grid_size: remains the same as the input grid.
output: substitute all the blue squares with red crosses. All other shapes (including the existing blue crosses) remain the same in the output grid.

input: a black background with a bunch of colored squares on it. You should also notice that only one of the colors has 4 squares.
grid_size: is the same size as the input grid.
output: draw two lines connecting both pairs of colored squares, all the way across the grid, same color as the squares  (for instance, if you noticed that you have 4 green squares on the input, on the output connect the ones on top and bottom edge of the grid with a green line, and the ones on left and right edge of the grid with a green line). If both sets of squares are on the top/bottom or left/right, connect the lines across the grid, not along the edge  (in other words, do not connect the two left squares or two top squares. Always connect the line to the opposite square). All other squares on your grid that are not your lines should be black.

input: a grid with two colors of randomly patterned blocks. Within the grid you will see some black 3x3 grids that are solid black.
grid_size: stays the same as the input grid.
output: Change all the black 3x3 grids to blue in the output grid.

input: 9 squares created by lines of grey
grid_size: is the same as the input grid size
output: take the 3x3 area with a yellow square and move it into a 3x3 area corresponding to where the yellow square is within the 9 squares. Then make all other squares within the other 9 squares black and any grey squares within the 9 squares black. The lines of grey stay.

input: a 3 by 3 grid
grid_size: changes to 3 by 6
output: copy the grid and reflect it on the other half.

input: a shape like the head of an arrow surrounded by black with single blocks of a different color randomly spaced around the outside of the grid.
grid_size: remains the same
output: Using the color of the random blocks around the outside, make a row straight down from the arrow head figure to meet any colored blocks below, extending the new row to the end of the grid

input: a large section of the same color
grid_size: is the same size
output: fill in the area of the large section with red to make a rectangular section. Background remain the same color

input: a 3x3 grid that may have between 1 and 3 colors.
grid_size: it stays the same.
output: place 3 grey boxes in various spots based on how many colors there are in the input grid. If there is one color, put 3 grey boxes on the top of the grid. If there are two colors, place a diagonal line of grey boxes form top left to bottom right. If there are 3 colors, place a diagonal line of grey boxes going from bottom left to top right.

input: the grey shapes
grid_size: same as the input grid.
output: count the 4 grid shape and color it with blue in the output and follow the same for 2 grid with green and 3 grid with red.

input: a small multi colored grid and a larger rectangle of that is one color plus BLACK
grid_size: the same as the small multi colored grid
output: replicate the smaller grid. Change the colors to black where they are black in the larger rectangle

input: A black grid
grid_size: Same as the input grid
output: You should create light blue border around the black grid.

input: a 3x3 pattern.
grid_size: is 3x6 vertical grid.
output: place the input grid in the top 3x3 space and create a mirror image in the bottom 3x3 space.

input: shapes (exemplars) composed of colored pixels and nonconnected pixels (singletons)
grid_size: it's the same as the original.
output: Copy the input grid. Add colored pixels to the singletons such that they copy the exemplars.

input: several different shapes on a large grid
grid_size: is the size of one of the shapes by itself
output: copy one of the shapes by itself and keep the black squares if there are any

input: a black background with a red zig-zag pattern.
grid_size: is the same as the original.
output: fill in every third triangle with yellow, starting at the lower-left: yellow, black, black, yellow.

input: a colored object with another colored object in it.
grid_size: is the size of the large colored object
output: copy the large colored object with smaller colored object in it. Then mirror the small colored object left to right.

input: 2 or 3 colors with a gray squares
grid_size: remains the same
output: rotate it 90 degree clockwise and mirror the result

input: a 8x8 grid with a black background and 4 distinct quadrants.  The top left quadrant should have a yellow pattern,   the top right quadrant should have a gray pattern,   the bottom left should have a pink pattern,  the bottom right should have a brown pattern.
grid_size: becomes 4x4.
output: resize the output grid to 4x4. Copy the top-left (yellow) pattern. Then, superimpose the bottom-right (brown) pattern on top. Then, superimpose the bottom-left pattern (pink) on top. Then, superimpose the top-right (gray) pattern on top.

input: two colored objects, one above the other.
grid_size: is identical.
output: create a mirror image of the top shape and place it to the side of that shape.

input: shapes surrounded by a complete gray border
grid_size: stays the same
output: change the color of the shape or shapes that match the shape inside the complete gray border so that they are the same color. That is the color of the shape that is identical in size to the one in the gray, will change to the same color as the one in the gray.

input: light blue square surrounded by a dark blue border with colored squares in each far corner.
grid_size: changes to the size of the interior light blue square
output: zoom in to the light blue square and change the light blue squares to the color or the exterior corner color that they are closest to.

input: several different colors
grid_size: that can contain one square of each color
output: put each color in one square that match their position in the big picture

input: a 3x3 grid with between 1 to 4 blue squares in it.
grid_size: is the same size as the input grid.
output: count the number of blue squares in the input. You will need this same number of squares in the output, but the new squares will become red and will be relocated in the following order until you have used the same number of squares that you counted; First red square goes in top left; second red square (if any) goes if top middle; third red square (if any) goes in top right and fourth red square (if any) goes in middle of grid.

input: a shape on a black background
grid_size: is the same.
output: keep the shape color the same. Fill any areas contained within the shape red and flood the black background with green.

input: colored squares
grid_size: half the input. Cut the long way in half.
output: copy one half of the input.

input: a grid with one light blue row and column. There is a one-colored design in one area and a multi-colored 2x2 grid in another area.
grid_size: will be 6x6.
output: fill in the entire grid with black. You then need to use each of the colors from the 2x2 grid to make the same design as the green design shown in the input grid. The colors must be in the same area shown in the 2x2 area. Each area will be a 3x3 grid, so there are a total of 4 3x3 grids. If the upper right square in the input pair is pink, then the design in the upper right 3x3 grid should be pink. Repeat the color blocks for the other 3x3 areas.

input: a center block with two edges going out
grid_size: is the same
output: continue the single block diagonally to the edge with the same color

input: a 23x23 grid with a black background. There will also be random yellow boxes scattered around. Some of the yellow boxes will be surrounded with blue boxes.
output: copy and paste the exact same grid. Find all instances of the pattern that is surrounded in blue. Everywhere on the grid where there is the exact yellow pattern, surround it with blue. So, on all sides of the yellow boxes (in the same pattern) will be blue boxes  (exactly as shown in the yellow/blue pattern).

input: rectangular colored shapes on a black background with blue pixels placed randomly
grid_size: is the same as the input grid
output: replace the blue pixels with pixels of the same color as the majority of surrounding pixels

input: solid colored shapes and some are block with some single pixel. A single color is for each pair.
grid_size: the same number
output: always remove a single pixel outside of the big blocks. Your output with be big blocks only, no scattered single pixels. Simply remove these single pixels and leave the complete major blocks whether these pixels are right next to or by themselves out in space. That's all.

input: a small section of the the final output pattern
grid_size: is 6x6
output: copy the original 3x3 pattern and replicate it after you rotate it clockwise onto the output. The top left 3x3 section should be a the same as the input. Then replicate and rotate to the right of this in the 3x3 section to the left, continue this until you have replicate and rotate 3 times total.

input: a design pattern on a black background
grid_size: 9x9 or the size of the design pattern
output: repeat the shape of the design pattern in 3x3 squares and make the same design on the 9x9 grid out of 3x3 squares.

input: a black background with a variety of blue shapes.
grid_size: is the same as the input.
output: copy the input grid. Then, any shapes that are closed (like complete squares or rectangles) will be changed from blue to green. Any other shapes that are open (incomplete) or are just lines, stay blue.

input: one complete line and at least one incomplete line. Each line is made of two colors.
grid_size: is the same as the input.
output: copy the input grid. Then, you have to complete each incomplete line. Maintain the lines color scheme while matching the pattern of the single complete line.

input: an array of black squares separated by a partially broken grid of colored lines.
grid_size: is identical to the input grid.
output: for every black square that has fully solid borders, recolor from black to green. For every square that has broken borders, recolor from black to yellow. Leave border lines in the original color.

input: one square that's not yellow
grid_size: stays the same
output: move the square that's not yellow down one space. Then create a yellow line above the square to the top of the grid. Next, leave a black column on both sides of the yellow. Then, make identical yellow columns using this pattern.

input: two vertical line shapes with yellow squares at the top and bottom, and two other shapes that join together with colors that match the middle part of the vertical line shapes.
grid_size: the height is the same as the height of the vertical line shapes. The width is the same width as the grid between the vertical line shapes plus the two yellow squares.
output: First, create a black grid according to the output grid size. Next, draw the vertical line shapes on the output grid identical to those on the input grid, and the space between the shapes should be the same too. Then, draw the other two shapes that join together in the middle of the grid, making sure that their colors match the colors of the middle part of the vertical line shapes. If the original color arrangement of the other shapes do not match the vertical line shapes, you need to flip the other shapes and draw them mirroring the original pattern so they match the color of the vertical line shapes. Note that the other two join shapes have to be drawn in the middle of the grid and nothing should be drawn on the grid where the yellow squares are.

input: black tiles placed in blocks of color
grid_size: stays the same
output: make the black tiles into lines that end at the color blocks they are in. if the color blocks appear vertically then the black lines should be horizontally. if the color blocks appear horizontally then the black lines should be vertical.

input: a grid with different colored square borders that get smaller and smaller until it reaches the center.
grid_size: same size as the input grid.
output: replace the inner most color with the outer most color and complete the same step with every color until all have been changed. In other words, invert the order of the colors.

input: a black grid with five blue-border squares.
grid_size: stays the same.
output: fill the squares with an even number grid INSIDE the blue border with red, and the rest (1x1, 3x3, 5x5) squares with the color you get from red yellow.

input: a single colored grid within a large grid. The single colored grid will contain a second color block or blocks.
grid_size: must be the same size as the large single colored grid.
output: fill in the entire row and column with the same color of the smaller cell. For example, if you have three single colored cells, you should end up with three columns and three rows.

input: a multi-colored 3x3 shape and a single gray square on a black background.
grid_size: is the same as the input grid size.
output: copy the input. Then, copy the colorful shape and paste it on top of the gray square, making sure the center of the shape is directly above the square.

input: squares of black and another color.
grid_size: will be 2x2.
output: replicate one of the patterns in one of the corners. Bottom right, bottom left, top right, or top left.

input: a large grid with one shape with a black center
grid_size: the grid size is the same
output: count the number of black square in the center of the outlined shape. Somewhere else on the grid is a group of black square that has has the same arrangement, though there may be additional black squares as well. Replicate the original shape from the input grid using those black square as the center. There should be two identical shapes when you are done.

input: four yellow squares and boxes of color within these yellow corners as well as a shape outside the yellow corner squares
grid_size: should be the yellow squares and within only
output: recreate the pattern outside the yellow corner squares within the yellow corner squares with provided starting shapes.

input: a 3x3 grid. some of the squares are filled with blue, and the rest are filled with black.
grid_size: the height would be double the input and the width would remain the same. It will be a 3x6 grid.
output: fill the top of the grid with the same as original. And fill the bottom of the grid with a mirror image of the original.

input: four black box and two colored box
grid_size: doubled in back twice in down
output: add reverse input on the back then do two more time.

input: a square with a gray line and blue and red tiles
grid_size: stays the same
output: complete a line with the colors. If it's red, fill the line in until you hit the gray bar. If it's blue, fill in until you hit the bottom or top edge.

input: a black background with  a colored square and different colored lines.
grid_size: is the same size as the colored square.
output: repeat the color lines in the same horizontal or vertical order as they appear in the input. The lines should go all the way across the grid to form stripes that are in the same color order and orientation as the input.

input: colored square and two black squares
grid_size: size remains the same
output: have the first remain the same then the second black square  have the same colors just move it 90 degrees and for the third black square change it 90 more degrees

input: a pattern in the center
grid_size: keep size the same
output: copy the pattern for the whole grid to match the center pattern.

input: 2 colors on a black background
grid_size: choose the shape with the most red squares and make the grid that size
output: replicate the pattern of the chosen shape.

input: in a black background a rectangle or square created from other colored rectangle or squares.
grid_size: new grid size should be the least number of squares necessary to create a similar, but not always the same, pattern of the colored rectangle or square.
output: consider only the colored part of the input. Create a similar square or rectangle, using the least number of squares.

input: a line at the top and two  start of lines at the bottom
grid_size: is the same
output: finish the line so that it is the same as the top line but finish the line in dark blue.

input: single colored squares
grid_size: in the same as the input
output: surround any green squares with pink squares,  surround any light blue squares with yellow squares,  and surround any red squares with dark blue squares.

input: A large grid with many colors, with a 4x3 box of one color.
grid_size: The grid size stays the same.
output: Turn everything black except for the 4x3 box of one color.

input: 3x3 grid
grid_size: 9x9 grid
output: each tile in the input grid is a 3x3 grid pattern on the output. Keep same color and pattern but increase to a 9x9 grid.

input: 4 grey squares and a colored rectangle within the dots.
grid_size: is the same as the input grid.
output: copy the input grid. Then, using the color of the colored rectangle, make the largest rectangle possible that will fit inside the four grey dots. The outside of the new rectangle should touch the inside of all four grey dots.

input: a 6x6 grid with a 2x2 colored square, where each corner of the square is a different color.
grid_size: is the same as the input grid size.
output: copy the input grid. Then, you will add 4 2x2 blocks to the grid, each touching the corner of the 2x2 colored square in the input. The color of each 2x2 block should be the same color as the opposite corner of the 2x2 colored square. If the 2x2 colored square is not in the center of the input, some of the 2x2 blocks you are adding may be off the page.

input: a gray grid breaking up the input into many sections.
grid_size: is the same as the input grid.
output: copy the input. Then, use blue flood fill to fill in the upper-left-most section. Then, use green and flood fill to fill in the bottom-right-most section. Then, use red and flood fill to fill in the center-most section.

input: is a 4x8 grid. The top 4x4 is a pattern of green pixels. The bottom is a 4x4 is a pattern of blue pixels.
grid_size: is a 4x4 grid.
output: overlay the top 4x4 grid of green pixels over the bottom 4x4 grid of blue pixels or vice versa. After you complete the overlay whichever pixels are still black will be changed to red in the output. All the other pixels which are green, blue, or both will be changed to black.

input: a grid with a square or rectangle composed of monochromatic pixels with a colored pixel at each of the interior corners of the rectangle.
grid_size: is the same as the input.
output: copy the input grid to the output workspace. Move each of the interior corner colored pixels to the exterior corner opposite of their input position. Meaning, move the upper left interior pixel such that its corner is touching the lower left corner of the lower left corner pixel of the monochromatic rectangle or square. You're moving pixel at a 45 degree angle to the exterior opposite corner, do that with each interior corner square to create the correct output grid.

input: more than one color set
grid_size: no change
output: replace minority colors with gray.

input: a series of gray squares
grid_size: is the same as the input
output: surround each square with the following, connected diagonally to each of the corners: Blue on the top left, Red on the top right, Green on the bottom left, Yellow on the bottom right. The end result should almost resemble a flower, with a gray center and four colored petals.

input: a black grid with a repeating pattern from left to right.
grid_size: double the original horizontal size with the same vertical size.
output: Repeat the middle colors in the second half of the new grid on the same rows.

input: a grid with randomly placed colored tiles
grid_size: remains the same as the input grid.
output: alternate to the RIGHT of the colored tile with light grey and the original color UNTIL it reaches the rightmost side of the grid, REPEAT this for each applicable colored tile.

input: a large grid with a red grid with black blocks missing. As well as small grid blocks with red blocks that fit the black blocks in the large grid.
grid_size: changes to the size of the large red grid.
output: fit the red blocks in the small grid blocks where they go on the large red grid with the colored blocks as well.

input: a two color pattern on a black background
grid_size: is the same size as input
output: remove the colored squares that create a floor to the other pattern. you bring the patterns together by moving the pattern that is the same color as the line you remove.

input: three 4x4 grey grids divide by black lines
grid_size: 3x3 grid
output: make three rows of three different solid colors corresponding to the grey 4x4 blocks. The first 4x4 block is the color of the top row, and so on. Grey 4x4 with a 2x2 black box in the middle = light blueGrey 4x4 with no black = redGrey 4x4 with black box center bottom = yellowGrey 4x4 with two 1x2 black lines on the left and right = green. If there are any more, they are a different color.

input: .a 4x4 square of blue and black boxes on top of a yellow line. Below the yellow line is a 4x4 square of red and black boxes.
grid_size: .should be 4x4.
output: compare the squares in the top and bottom 4x4 square. If they match (both black or both color) make the output square black. If they do not match, make the output square green.

input: colored blocks on a black background
grid_size: same as input
output: extend the colored blocks, using their original color, to the right and downward, creating "L" shapes. Start with the bottom-most block. Draw a line from the bottom-most block until it touches the right side of the grid, and then draw a line downward from there until it touches the bottom of the grid. This will form an inverted "L" shape that is facing left. Then, go up to the next colored block and repeat this process, except when you draw the line downward, stop where it would touch the first color. This will form another inverted "L" shape, on top of the first one. Do this for each colored block.

input: grid filled with different colors. No background color.
grid_size: width should be the number of colors. Height should be the number of the most....color.
output: in a black background, fill out the left with the most color, then the second most, third most, continue. Start it from the top.

input: a mirror pattern with colored blocks on one side split by a line of blocks from one corner to the other.
grid_size: stays the same.
output: take one side and mirror it to the other side.

input: can see a pattern with a some black part.
grid_size: should be the same size as the black spots
output: fill the black spots with the exact same pattern that need to be filled in the original grid.

input: a grid with several different colored blocks.
grid_size: stay the same.
output: copy the input and fill in any spaces that have with blue that have blue touching black.

input: a single-colored grid of symmetrical lines that intersect to create segmented boxes. The boxes are filled  and create a design.
grid_size: becomes smaller. Equal to the number of segmented boxes present in the input grid
output: avoid the lines that create the boxes, and instead  focus on the pattern. Copy the pattern so that it is mirrored horizontally (left to right). You should end up with only the design from the input.

input: a black grid with 4 pixels evenly spaced from each other to create a sort of square and a different colored collection of pixels that create a random shape.
grid_size: remains the same
output: think of the 4 pixels as a picture frame. Reposition the random shape to be centered in that frame.

input: two squares of different colors
grid_size: no change
output: connect the squares use light blue with a right angle

input: colored shapes against a black background
grid_size: will be the size that the output lines require.
output: identify the largest shapes by number of squares. This may be one shape or more than one shape, if they have the same number of square. Then create a vertical line for each of those shapes, in the order from left to right of the shapes, each line with the same number of squares as the input shape. If only one shape is largest, there will be one output line. If two shapes are largest together, there will be two lines, and so on.

input: a single blue point at the bottom
grid_size: is the same as the old one
output: draw a blue dot one to the right and one up from the original one, follow that pattern until you reach the side,  then draw a blue dot one to the left and one up until you reach the other side,  repeat until you reach the top.

input: a pattern using colored squares
grid_size: is twice as wide and the same height as the original
output: copy the pattern exactly to the new empty section. There should be two of the same pattern side-by-side.

input: a square made up of red boxes along with some gray boxes spread apart.
grid_size: stays the same size.
output: simply move the gray boxes toward the red boxes taking the most direct route possible. The gray boxes are then placed wherever they touch a red box in some way.

input: shapes with black inside and dot in center
grid_size: match the output
output: color the inside blue but if the border of shape goes outside the grid leave inside black.

input: diagonal lines of colored squares.
grid_size: is the same as the input.
output: change every other square on each of the diagonal lines to yellow (starting with the 2nd square on each line)

input: see 4 set of 3 blocks in 4 different colors.
grid_size: should be 4x4.
output: make a square with the each set of blocks. There should be a smaller black square in the center.

input: only vertical blocks which stay on rows 1, 3, 5, 7 and 9.
grid_size: will remain the same.
output: change the shortest colored blocks from gray to red and the tallest colored blocks from gray to blue. Change the remaining gray blocks to black.

input: area that appear not fill.
grid_size: stay the same.
output: fill not fill area with green, leaving black border.

input: a black grid with a small horizontal line in red.
grid_size: exactly the same as the input grid.
output: copy your red input boxes to the output grid. Make an exact same line (as red) in green, but also add  1 green box. Repeat moving up until your top portion is colored in green with -1 box moving downward. Go to the box(es) just BELOW your red line. Make a new line (or box) in blue, but -1 less blue box than the number of red box(es). Repeat this in blue until you only have ONE black box (row) left on the bottom. In the end  you will have green, red, blue and it will zig-zag getting smaller as you go down. Be sure to leave the very bottom row all black.

grid_size: a 9x9 grid

The corners should go in the corners. the t-shape should go at the top in the middle,  the upside down t-shape should go at the bottom in the middle,  the two side way t-shapes should go on the left and right side in the middle so that the long side is against to the left and right. Make sure to keep the same colors for each.

grid_size: is the same as the input grid size
output: fill yellow squares in the hole of the rectangle and also add yellow squares on either all of the horizontal or all of the vertical lines out of the hole. Then add more yellow squares on a diagonal starting from the inner corner of each hole and going to the edge of the grid. Some yellow squares will repeat the yellow squares to fill the hole.

input: a single red box and a single blue box. You should also see at least one orange box and at least one green box.
grid_size: is the same as the input grid size.
output: create 2 designs using all of the colored boxes in the input grid. One design is focused on the red box and the other one is focused on the blue box. Both the red box and the blue box will be in their exact same positions in the new grid. First put the red box in the same place as it is in the input grid. Now, look at the green boxes in the input grid and imagine that the green boxes are being pulled toward the red box until they are touching it. So, if there is a green box in the input grid above the red box, place it directly above the red box in the new grid. If there is a green box to the right of the red box in the input side, move it until it is directly to the right of the red box. Do the same for any other green boxes. After you are done, all of the green boxes should be touching the red box which is still in its original location. That design is done. Now use the same exact method for the blue box and surround it with the orange boxes. Think of the blue and red boxes as the centers of flowers and the green and orange boxes as the petals.
